Compare the results with time quantum 3 and time quantum 5. Which quantum gave better average waiting time? Why?
    A time quantum of 5ms resulted in a better (lower) average waiting time (5.00ms compared to 6.67ms for 3ms). 
    This happened because a larger time quantum allowed the shorter processes (Process 2 and Process 3) to finish 
    entirely in their first turn on the CPU, preventing them from being thrown to the back of the queue to wait 
    for another cycle.

2. What would happen if the time quantum was 1ms? Would the system be more or less efficient?
    The system would be highly responsive but less efficient. A 1ms quantum forces the CPU to constantly interrupt
    processes and swap them out. Every swap triggers a "context switch," which takes a tiny bit of processing power 
    itself. With a 1ms quantum, the CPU spends a disproportionate amount of its time just managing the line rather 
    than executing the actual programs.

3. What would happen if the time quantum was 20ms (larger than any process burst time)? How would Round Robin behave then?
    If the time quantum is larger than the longest burst time, no process is ever interrupted by the timer. Process 
    1 would finish completely, then Process 2, then Process 3. The Round Robin algorithm would behave identically to 
    a First-Come, First-Served (FCFS) scheduling algorithm.

4. In the simulation with quantum 3, how many context switches occurred? Count each time a process was removed from the queue.
    Based on the rule to count every time a process is removed from the queue to run, there are 6 occurrences
        P1 runs for 3ms (remaining: 4)
        P2 runs for 3ms (remaining: 1)
        P3 runs for 2ms (remaining: 0, finished)
        P1 runs for 3ms (remaining: 1)
        P2 runs for 1ms (remaining: 0, finished)
        P1 runs for 1ms (remaining: 0, finished)

5. Why does Round Robin prevent the convoy effect that occurs in FCFS scheduling?
    The convoy effect happens in FCFS when one massively long, CPU-heavy process gets to the front of the line and 
    forces all the quick, short processes to wait forever behind it. Round Robin prevents this by enforcing a strict 
    time limit (the quantum). Even if a massive process is at the front, it is forced to yield the CPU after its 
    time is up, allowing the shorter "convoy" of processes behind it to get their turn and clear out quickly.
